	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>July 19<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1849</date></p>
				<p>Dear <hi rend="underline"><addressee>I. Leeser</addressee></hi></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr. Bush</persName> mentioned several times<lb/> some of your remarks which convince me that<lb/> you know my name and I therefore need not<lb/> introduce myself.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Your remarks concerning <persName>Frank&#39;s</persName> Teffila<lb/> show that you <sic>dont</sic> understand my attitude<lb/> towards that work.  <persName>Mr. Frank</persName><add>&#63;</add> was recommended<lb/> to me as a poor but industrious Jew.  He asked<lb/> me to translate for him several German prayers<lb/> by <persName>Schlesinger</persName>.  I declined to do that because I hate<lb/> to do machine work but I promised <del>him</del> to write<lb/> a few original English prayers for him which I could<lb/> not do up to now because I did not have the<lb/> time.  I did not authorize <persName>Mr. Frank</persName> to mention<lb/> my name as translator.  I am not very keen to<lb/> <add>&#63;</add>and in the limelight and I know that this work<lb/> will stand my scrutiny.  If the Herald would<lb/> have continued to exist I would have published<lb/> my opinion about that long ago.  I shall<lb/> however wait till the work is ready and<lb/> then I shall give an explanation in the<lb/> introduction which will seem to you probably the</p>
			<pb n="2R"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">2</p>
				<p>only honorable way and which will protect <persName>Mr.<lb/> Frank</persName> to <sic>loose</sic> out&#44; as he would be ruined totally<lb/> otherwise.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">How and why your work <sic>compeats</sic> with<lb/> that of <persName>Mr. Frank</persName> is not my business&#44; nor do I<lb/> care&#44; as you probably have noticed by now.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">How about an answer to <persName>Mr. Becker&#39;s</persName><lb/> attack on the friends&#63;  Is justice asleep and<lb/> did your Occident become a party journal&#63;  Can the<lb/> friends patronize <hi rend="underline">your</hi> paper which attacks them in an<lb/> unmanly way and observes a long silence&#44; so that<lb/> a defense looks like the last ray of the sun before<lb/> the darkness of the night&#63;  Indeed you work slowly<lb/> to do justice to those who have a right to ask for<lb/> justice.  If you care to have subscribers among the<lb/> friends&#44; I think you should first try to heal the<lb/> wound which you inflicted or at least <sic>dont</sic> cause<lb/> the fruit of enemies<add>&#63;</add> which already prevails so<lb/> terribly among us.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">This letter&#44; <persName>Mr. Leeser</persName> is of<lb/> course strictly confidential and nothing may be<lb/> published.  My brother <persName>L. Waterman</persName> of <placeName>New<lb/> Haven Conn.</placeName> desires the occident.  <persName>Mr. Bush</persName> is<lb/> going to order it.</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Awaiting your reply I am</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">very truly yours&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Sig. Waterman</persName>&#44; M. D.</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)"><placeName>411 Grand Street</placeName></p>
		</body>
